What I Learned
1. Inline Style

CSS written directly inside an HTML tag using the style attribute
Only affects that one specific element
Highest priority вҖ” overrides all other CSS
Bad practice for large projects вҖ” hard to maintain
Example: <p style="color: red; font-size: 18px;">Hello</p>
Rule: avoid inline styles вҖ” use external CSS files instead


2. Color Property

Controls the color of text
Four ways to write colors:

Named: color: red
HEX: color: #e74c3c
RGB: color: rgb(231, 76, 60)
RGBA: color: rgba(231, 76, 60, 0.5) вҖ” last value is opacity


background-color вҖ” sets the background color of an element
HEX and RGB are most commonly used in real projects


3. Text Properties

font-size вҖ” size of the text вҖ” use px or rem
font-weight вҖ” thickness of text вҖ” normal, bold, or number (100вҖ“900)
font-family вҖ” typeface of text вҖ” always add fallback fonts
font-style вҖ” normal or italic
text-align вҖ” left, right, center, justify
text-decoration вҖ” underline, overline, line-through, none
text-transform вҖ” uppercase, lowercase, capitalize
letter-spacing вҖ” space between individual letters
line-height вҖ” space between lines of text
Example:

cssp {
  font-size: 16px;
  font-weight: 400;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
  text-align: center;
  line-height: 1.6;
}

4. Selectors

Selectors tell CSS which HTML element to style
Types practiced today:

SelectorSyntaxWhat it targetsElementpAll p tagsClass.boxAll elements with class boxID#titleOne element with id titleDescendantdiv pAll p inside any divChilddiv > pOnly direct p children of divAdjacent Siblingh1 + pFirst p immediately after h1

5. Class Selector

Targets elements using the class attribute
Written with a dot prefix: .classname
Same class can be used on multiple elements
One element can have multiple classes
Most used selector in real projects
Example:

css.card {
  background-color: white;
  padding: 20px;
  border-radius: 8px;
}
html<div class="card">Content</div>
<div class="card">Content</div>

6. ID Selector

Targets one specific element using the id attribute
Written with a hash prefix: #idname
ID must be unique вҖ” only one element per page can have the same ID
Higher specificity than class вҖ” overrides class styles
Example:

css#hero {
  background-color: #1a237e;
  color: white;
}
html<section id="hero">Main Banner</section>

Rule: use class for reusable styles, use ID only when the element is truly unique


7. Descendant Selector

Targets elements that are anywhere inside another element
Written with a space between selectors
Targets all matching descendants вҖ” not just direct children
Example:

cssdiv p {
  color: gray;
}

This targets ALL <p> tags inside ANY <div> вҖ” no matter how deeply nested


8. Adjacent Sibling Selector

Targets the element that comes immediately after another element
Written with a + between selectors
Both elements must share the same parent
Only targets the very first sibling вҖ” not all siblings after
Example:

cssh1 + p {
  font-size: 18px;
  color: gray;
}

This targets only the first <p> that comes directly after an <h1>


9. Child Combinator

Targets only the DIRECT children of an element
Written with a > between selectors
More specific than descendant selector
Does not target grandchildren or deeper nested elements
Example:

cssul > li {
  color: blue;
}

This targets only <li> that are direct children of <ul>
Key difference from descendant: descendant targets all levels, child targets only one level deep


10. Box Model

Every HTML element is a rectangular box
The box model has 4 layers from inside to outside:

Content вҖ” the actual text or image
Padding вҖ” space between content and border
Border вҖ” the line around the padding
Margin вҖ” space outside the border between elements


Understanding box model is essential for layout

